ing WWII, and the National World War II Memorial have not only transformed the physical space of the Mall but have also dramatically rewritten ideas about U.S. nationalism expressed there. In Sacrificing Soldiers on the National Mall, Kristin Ann Hass examines this war memorial boom, the debates about war and race and gender and patriotism that shaped the memorials, and the new narratives about the nature of American citizenship that they spawned. Sacrificing Soldiers on the National Mall explores the meanings we have made in exchange for the lives of our soldiers and asks if we have made good on our enormous responsibility to them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCollective memoryzUnited States. 0aKorean War Veterans Memorial (Washington, D.C.). 0aMemorializationzUnited States. 0aNational Japanese American Memorial to Patriotism (Washington, D.C.). 0aWar memorialszWashington (D.C.). 0aWorld War II Memorial (Washington, D.C.). 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aamerica.  aamerican citizenship.  aamerican wars.  acultural critique.  ahistorians.  akorean war veterans memorial.  amilitary service.  anational japanese american memorial to patriotism during wwii.  anational mall.  anational memory.  anational world war ii memorial.  anonfiction.  apatriotism.  apolitical science.  apolitics.  asoldiers.  aunited states.  aus capital.  aus nationalism.  avietnam veterans memorial.  awar memorials.  awashington dc.  awomen in military service for america memorial.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027410540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095475540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520954755423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn